dataIdInfo.idAbs: An encumbrance is a legal claim, right, or liability held by a third party on a piece of property that is not an ownership interest in the property, but limits how the owner can use or manage the property. Encumbrances can include liens placed against the property, deed restrictions, covenants, easements, encroachments, leases, and licenses. Most encumbrances are attached to the property and remain in effect when property ownership is transferred.
dataIdInfo.idCredit: Washington State Department of Natural Resources (WADNR)
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The Right of Way and Forest Roads Sections of the State of Washington, Department of Natural Resources (DNR) developed the encumbrance feature class to record the spatial location and attributes of DNR’s right of way easements. This layer is used for planning, analysis and mapping purposes.
